def generate_wordcloud(text):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width = 800, height = 800, 
                background_color ='white', 
                stopwords = None, 
                min_font_size = 10).generate(' '.join(text))
    return wordcloud

In [15]:
def generate_wordcloud(tokens, title):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width=800, height=800, background_color='white', min_font_size=10).generate(' '.join(tokens))
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8), facecolor=None)
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.tight_layout(pad=0)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

def flatten_list(list_of_lists):
    return [item for sublist in list_of_lists for item in sublist]

In analyzing the Hotel reviews dataset, we employed a multiword tokenizer MWT to preprocess the text data, enabling a more comprehensive understanding of the reviews. After tokenization, we segregated the reviews based on their overall ratings, focusing on reviews rated either 1 or 5 stars. Subsequently, we generated word clouds for both positive (5-star) and negative (1-star) reviews to visualize the most frequent terms used within each category. The word clouds revealed distinct patterns in the language used by customers in their evaluations.

Positive reviews commonly highlighted words associated with satisfaction and positive experiences, such as "comfortable," "clean", "helpful", "friendly staff" and "service".

Conversely, negative reviews exhibited a prevalence of terms indicating dissatisfaction or problems encountered during the stay, including "terrible," "bathrooms", "rude" and "broken." Overall, the word clouds provided valuable insights into the key aspects that contribute to guests' perceptions of their hotel experiences, facilitating a deeper understanding of customer sentiment and areas for potential improvement in hospitality services.
